  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions against money laundering. These laws aim to combat money laundering on a global scale by establishing standards for national legislation and promoting international cooperation. Here are some key examples:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** Also known as the Vienna Convention, it was one of the first international treaties to explicitly address money laundering. It requires signatory countries to criminalize the laundering of drug-related proceeds and to cooperate in international investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** Also known as the Palermo Convention, it expands the scope of the Vienna Convention to cover the laundering of proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes, including corruption, trafficking in persons, and arms smuggling.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003):** Also known as the Merida Convention, it focuses on preventing and combating corruption, including the laundering of proceeds derived from corrupt acts.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty, the FATF Recommendations are the global standard for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. They provide a comprehensive framework of measures that countries should implement, covering areas such as criminalization of money laundering, customer due diligence, record-keeping, and international cooperation. FATF's recommendations are widely adopted and implemented by countries around the world.\n\n*   **Regional Conventions and Agreements:** In addition to the UN conventions, several regional bodies have adopted conventions and agreements to combat money laundering, such as the Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure and Confiscation of the Proceeds from Crime.\n\nThese international laws and standards serve as a foundation for national anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations. They encourage countries to criminalize money laundering, establish financial intelligence units, implement know-your-customer rules, and cooperate internationally in investigations and asset recovery.",
